Usually I enjoy the food @Blossom Tree in downtown Atlanta. However, on February 16, 2021, I placed an order for (Beef Kimchi Rice) for pickup through the Ritual app. The app stated my food would be ready at 3:43 pm. I arrived there a few minutes early and my order was ready and handed to me. I didn’t check my food. When I got home (15 min drive). I opened the container and was mortified. The meat was barely lukewarm (it was dry) and there was no kimchi in sight. Nothing. No green onions. The dumplings were tough and the sauce must’ve been left in the pot. If at the end of the day, Blossom Tree wasn’t able to serve me what I paid for, a hot meal worth eating they should’ve denied the order. The food was awful. I won’t be going back to Blossom Tree for a long time if at all. This has left a bad tast toward this restaurant. A total waste of my time, energy and money

There's a plethora of Asian ethnic restaurants downtown that are bomb and serve bomb food, and Blossom Tree by no means falls short of maintaining that standard. And the location is pretty small, so if you're claustrophobic, you're gonna have to be okay with being shoulder to shoulder with people for a couple minutes while waiting on your food (which probably won't be more than 15 minutes their chefs put meals out at supersonic speeds)  My go - to is typically a beef of pork bibimbap bowl accompanied by kimchi and dumplings or soup. It's rice and salad and deliciously seasoned protein that'll keep you coming back for more on the regular.  I've also tried their tacos and crispy chicken curry bowl which are great as well, but nothing is topping the bibimbap section of the menu.

Disclaimer: I lived in Korea for 16 months and am a Korean food fanatic.  I knew that I'd be taking a risk by coming here, but I wanted to give it a try.  I'd be willing to give Blossom Tree one more go, but it didn't live up to my expectations.  If you like Asian food adventures, feel free to check this place out; I was just looking for authenticity and didn't find it.  --  Galbi bibimbap with spicy sauce: The girl who took my order told me the spicy sauce is the more authentic option (usually you don't get a choice of sauces in Korea), so that's what I got.  The sauce did remind me of the real thing, and the galbi meat sort of reminded me of the real thing, but that was about as close as the similarities got.  I admit I'm being super picky here, but bibimbap is supposed to come in a bowl, not on a plate.  There was too much sauce, too much meat, and not enough rice.  The vegetables didn't mesh well with the dish, either.  Korean dumplings: They tasted and felt like they'd been frozen before and that they had been reheated a long time before they made it to my plate.  I think I ate two out of the three I'd been given.  I wasn't impressed.  Sweet potato: My first bite was nice.  Crispy on the outside, soft on the inside.  But sweet sauce over the potatoes quickly became too much for me, though.  I ate about half of my portion.  --  Very friendly service.  Casual atmosphere.  I think I'll give it one more shot, but with the amazing Dua just down the street, I don't know when I'll be making the decision to visit Blossom Tree again.

While staying in DT Atlanta, and in need of takeout, preferably good takeout, we found Blossom Tree. We placed our order online as you cannot order by phone. My husband walked the two blocks over and was back in less time than I expected since the food was ready right on time. We opened the takeout right away, less than 15 minutes, everything was hot, crispy, and fresh.  I ordered the pork bibimbap with mild sauce (very mild, hot was described as siracha). There was an ample portion of lean tender pork, the greens were fresh, and the rice was recently steamed (dried out rice is a pet peeve). Most dishes come with two sides, I ordered the dumplings (surprisingly crispy and good proportion of meat to wrapper) and the kimchi (very mild).  Husband ordered the beef rice. Based on the rate of inhalation, it was a hit.  Wish we would have enjoyed the meal in the restaurant but we were incredibly pleased with the choice!

I finally had a chance to check this place out, and I enjoyed it. I went with the Taco Plate which gives you 3 tacos and 2 sides - definitely a bargain for $10. It took a great coworker of mine to introduce me to this place.  Why have I never heard of it or paid much attention to it???  Since the closing of Pixel's Cafe I have been in need of a Korean lunch fix.  Looks like I have been lucky enough to find it!  Food:  I ordered the Bulgogi/rice plate with dumplings and sweet potatoes on the side.  The bulgogi was very thinly sliced beef (almost shredded like) with onions, scallions, and mushroom.  There is an enormous proportion of meat that tops the white rice.  It was flavorful and savory compared to the sweetness offered at Pixel's.  None the less I was pleased.  The dumplings were a bit too greasy for my liking but they were nicely flavored.  The sweet potatoes as so many other reviews have spoke about are awesome.  Perfectly cooked then drenched in a sweet sauce.  This place had mega yum factor for me.  Service:  I went during the lunch hour so the place was pretty crowded but we managed to get a seat (surprisingly).  You walk up to the counter, place your order then wait to be called or they will bring it to you.  The place was so busy I hardly noticed the service.  It was more of a "Wam, Bam, Thank You Ma'am" type setting.  Our food was ready pretty quickly and staff is helpful in explaining the menu.  I have no real complains because it was very informal.  That being said there is no need to speak about atmosphere.  There are tables and chairs and lots of people.  :)  Will I be a frequent customer? Hell yes!

I went with a group of 5 for lunch, and while it was busy we were able to grab a seat quickly.  The food and service were both spectacular, we're all looking forwards to our next visit soon.  (I recommend the beef bibimbob with dumplings and sweet potatoes!)
